<body>
  <div type="orginaltweet">
    <p>Forces that fragment/hinder the <choice><sic>black</sic><corr>Black></corr></choice> community: <choice><sic>Police</sic><corr>police></corr></choice> brutality, prison industrial complex, mass incarceration, media feminization aand criminalization of the <choice><sic>black</sic><corr>Black</corr></choice> man, social welfare programs conditional on absent father, health <choice><sic>&amp;</sic><corr>and</corr></choice> mental health inequity, interracial coupling<add>.</add></p>
  <div type="reply">
    <p>The media plays a huge role in ensuring that the feminization and criminalization of the <choice><sic>black</sic><corr>Black></corr></choice> man is a perpetuating cycle. We've all seen how the news will use a mugshot for the innocent <choice><sic>black</sic><corr>Black></corr></choice> man slain by police while using a picture of the <choice><sic>white</sic><corr>White></corr></choice> mass shooter petting a kitten<add>.</add></p>
  <div type="reply">
    <p>If the media isn't portraying the <choice><sic>black</sic><corr>Black></corr></choice> man as a oversexualized, dangerous or ciminal, he's being portrayed as homosexual. Outside of that, the only time we see <choice><sic>blacks</sic><corr>Blacks></corr></choice> portrayed positively in the media is when we're singing, dancing or entertaining <choice><sic>wh*te</sic><corr>White></corr></choice> folks in the sports arena<add>.</add></p>
  </div>
</div>
